<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,1040]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,151,176]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species can be separated from other 
<taxonomicName box="[774,939,151,175]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Pepsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[774,847,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Pepsis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[983,1153,151,175]" name="Dominican Republic" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">the Dominican</collectingCountry>
Republic by having the integument black with purplish-blue reflections (
<figureCitation box="[695,781,188,212]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1014,1037]" captionTargetBox="[261,1325,193,993]" captionTargetId="figure-57@40.[261,1325,193,993]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 3. A, D. Pepsis rubra: habitus, dorsal view: A. ♂; D. ♀. B–C. Pepsis ruficornis: habitus, dorsal view: B. ♂; C. ♀. E. Pepsis marginata: habitus, dorsal view, ♀." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5251736" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5251736/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
), except on the propodeum, some specimens can also have greenish reflections. Additionally, the pubescence on the body is long and black, abundant on the propodeum; the pronotum has the collar differentiated from the disc; the front basitarsus is weakly spined, the spines are in two rows; the wing has the edge of first radial 2 cell rounded; and the fore and hind wings are yellow with dark margins (
<figureCitation box="[159,250,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1349,1372]" captionTargetBox="[210,1376,193,1328]" captionTargetId="figure-111@39.[210,1376,193,1328]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 2. A. Pepsis marginata: hind and fore wing, dorsal view, ♀. B. Auplopus bellus: propodeum, lateral view, ♂.C. Drepanaporus collaris: hind and fore wing, dorsal view, ♀. D. Anoplius fulgidus: fore and hind wing, dorsal view, ♀. E. Tachypompilus ferrugineus: fore wing, dorsal view, ♀. F. Anoplius americanus ambiguus: fore wing, dorsal view, ♀. G. Anoplius hispaniolae: fore wing, dorsal view, ♀. H. Drepanaporus antillarum: fore wing, ♀. I. Dipogon marlowei sp. nov.: fore wing, ♀." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5251734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5251734/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). The female (
<figureCitation box="[416,501,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1014,1037]" captionTargetBox="[261,1325,193,993]" captionTargetId="figure-57@40.[261,1325,193,993]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 3. A, D. Pepsis rubra: habitus, dorsal view: A. ♂; D. ♀. B–C. Pepsis ruficornis: habitus, dorsal view: B. ♂; C. ♀. E. Pepsis marginata: habitus, dorsal view, ♀." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5251736" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5251736/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
) has the antenna black, the apices of antennal segment 3 onwards dull orange; the hind tibia is spinose with teeth narrow and sharp, and with short and dense pilosity between them. The male has the antenna black and the dorsal face of the hind tibia is not spinose.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
