.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,1040]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,691,716]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="1">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is endemic to, and distributed throughout, the Caribbean. 
<bibRefCitation author="Vardy, C. R." box="[1167,1320,692,716]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 133" refId="ref45803" refString="Vardy, C. R. (2002) The New World tarantula-hawk wasp genus Pepsis Fabricius (Hymenoptera: Pompilidae), Part 2. The P. grossa - to P. deurata - groups. Zoologische Verhandelinden, 338, 1 - 133." type="journal article" year="2002">Vardy (2002)</bibRefCitation>
, however, was not confident in the locality labels for the specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[895,1070,727,751]" name="Trinidad Island" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Trinidad Island</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1132,1224,728,751]" name="Panama" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Panama</collectingCountry>
. It might occur in southern Florida as well (
<bibRefCitation author="Vardy, C. R." box="[435,572,764,788]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 133" refId="ref45803" refString="Vardy, C. R. (2002) The New World tarantula-hawk wasp genus Pepsis Fabricius (Hymenoptera: Pompilidae), Part 2. The P. grossa - to P. deurata - groups. Zoologische Verhandelinden, 338, 1 - 133." type="journal article" year="2002">Vardy 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,1040]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,800,824]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Host.</emphasis>
Records of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Palisot de Beauvois" authorityYear="1809" box="[400,544,800,824]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Pepsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis box="[400,544,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. marginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[615,749,799,823]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
made by Petrunkevich (1926, 
<emphasis box="[1097,1153,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">apud</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Snelling, R. R. &amp; Torres, J. A." box="[1161,1429,799,823]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="356 - 376" refId="ref45561" refString="Snelling, R. R. &amp; Torres, J. A. (2004) The spider wasps of Puerto Rico and the British Virgin Islands (Hymenoptera: Pompilidae). Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 77, 356 - 376." type="journal article" year="2004">Snelling &amp; Torres 2004</bibRefCitation>
) refer to 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamberlin" authorityName="Chamberlin" box="[239,636,836,860]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Crytopholis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="portoricae">
<emphasis box="[239,496,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Crytopholis portoricae</emphasis>
Chamberlin
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[650,819,836,860]" class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Theraphosidae</taxonomicName>
) as the only prey of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,1040]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,872,896]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
Females of this species can capture spiders eight to ten times their own weight (
<bibRefCitation author="Laing, D. J." box="[1285,1424,871,895]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 21" refId="ref44731" refString="Laing, D. J. (1979) Studies on populations of the tunnel web spider Porrhothele antipodiana (Mygalomorphae: Dipluridae) - Part I: Relationship with hunting wasps (Pompilidae). Tuatara, 24, 1 - 21." type="journal article" year="1979">Laing 1979</bibRefCitation>
). Specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Palisot de Beauvois" authorityYear="1809" box="[311,455,909,932]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Pepsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis box="[311,455,909,932]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. marginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are distinguished from the sympatric species 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Drury" baseAuthorityYear="1773" box="[973,1066,908,932]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Pepsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubra">
<emphasis box="[973,1066,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. rubra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by lacking the white apex in the fore wing, and from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[391,531,944,968]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Pepsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ruficornis">
<emphasis box="[391,531,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. ruficornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having yellow, apically darkened wings. 
<bibRefCitation author="Vardy, C. R." box="[1047,1198,943,967]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 133" refId="ref45803" refString="Vardy, C. R. (2002) The New World tarantula-hawk wasp genus Pepsis Fabricius (Hymenoptera: Pompilidae), Part 2. The P. grossa - to P. deurata - groups. Zoologische Verhandelinden, 338, 1 - 133." type="journal article" year="2002">Vardy (2002)</bibRefCitation>
discussed additional characters for distinguishing females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Palisot de Beauvois" authorityYear="1809" box="[602,746,981,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Pepsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis box="[602,746,981,1004]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. marginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, such as the absence of lateral extension of the groove on the second metasomal segment. Specimens of this species are very large, varying from 
<quantity box="[1086,1210,1016,1040]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.75" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="37.5" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="25.0">25–50 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
